This change cannot possibly have been subject to this statement:

So I wonder: How much of this PR is generated from the changes to `kem_scheme.c` and `sig_scheme.c` and how much is manual?

pull_request.title: Solve '-Wstrict-prototypes' for clang >= 15.0
pull_request.body:
Since clang 15, the warning '[-Wstrict-prototypes](https://clang.llvm.org/docs/DiagnosticsReference.html#wstrict-prototypes)' is now triggered by a missing
prototype in a declaration. For example:

```c
int foo() {
}
```

triggers the warning '-Wstrict-prototypes', because `foo` needs a prototype:

```c
int foo(void) {
}
```

liboqs do have several functions without prototypes. Since clang 15, it breaks
the compilation.

This PR adds the `void` parameter for functions without arguments.

Note: this warning is not enabled by GCC.

comment.body:
> It would be good to get these changes into the Frodo upstream; we don't need to wait for this, we can push them there afterwards.

OK, then those changes are good, too.

The question is whether we should (manually) retain/reinstate them or whether we should now "move" on them (removing Rainbow for good, say). If the latter, this PR truly can be merged and I volunteer to do a PR to remove Rainbow :-)
